let grid = [];
let rows = 800;
let cols = 800;
let cellSize = 10;
let generations = 0;
let speed = 10;

function setup() {
  createCanvas(800, 800);
  background(0);
  for (let i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
    grid[i] = [];
    for (let j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
      grid[i][j] = random(2);
    }
  }
}

function draw() {
  background(0);
  for (let i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
      if (grid[i][j] === 1) {
        fill(255);
      } else {
        fill(0);
      }
      rect(j * cellSize, i * cellSize, cellSize, cellSize);
    }
  }
  generations++;
  if (generations % speed === 0) {
    for (let i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
      for (let j = 0; j < cols; j++) {
        let neighbors = countNeighbors(i, j);
        if (grid[i][j] === 1 && (neighbors < 2 || neighbors > 3)) {
          grid[i][j] = 0;
        } else if (grid[i][j] === 0 && neighbors === 3) {
          grid[i][j] = 1;
        }
      }
    }
  }
}

function countNeighbors(i, j) {
  let neighbors = 0;
  for (let x = -1; x <= 1; x++) {
    for (let y = -1; y <= 1; y++) {
      if (x === 0 && y === 0) continue;
      let col = (j + y + cols) % cols;
      let row = (i + x + rows) % rows;
      neighbors += grid[row][col];
    }
  }
  return neighbors;
}
```

Here's a TypeScript function that analyzes the given text and returns an array of variables along with their types:

```typescript
function analyzeText(text: string): { [key: string]: string }[] {
    const result: { [key: string]: string }[] = [];
    const pattern = /"([^"]+)":?(\w+)?/g;
    let match: RegExpExecArray | null;

    while ((match = pattern.exec(text))!== null) {
        const variable = match[1];
        const type = match[2] || 'text';

        result.push({ variable, type });
    }

    return result;
}

// Example usage:
const text = `Welcome to the world, "something:text", "longText:textarea", and "thingie:number". but, there may also be anything like "blah."`;

console.log(analyzeText(text));
// Output:
// [
//   { variable: "something", type: "text" },
//   { variable: "longText", type: "textarea" },
//   { variable: "thingie", type: "number" },
//   { variable: "blah", type: "text" }
// ]
```

This function uses a regular expression to match the variables and their types in the text. The pattern `/"([^"]+)":?(\w+)?/g` breaks down as follows:

- `/"`: Matches a double quote.
- `([^"]+)`: Captures one or more characters that are not double quotes (this is the variable name).
- `":?`: Matches a colon optionally (for variables like "longText:textarea").
- `(\w+)`: Captures one or more word characters (letters, numbers, underscores) (this is the variable type).
- `g`: The `g` flag at the end of the pattern makes the match global, so all occurrences are found.

The function then loops through all matches, constructs an object with the variable and its type, and adds it to the result array. If a variable does not have a type specified, the type is set to "text" by default.

Here's a JavaScript function that will wrap each gift with the given algorithm. This function will use a simple string manipulation technique to create the wrapping paper effect.

```javascript
/**
 * Wraps each gift with the given algorithm.
 * 
 * @param {string[]} gifts - An array of gift strings.
 * @returns {string[]} An array of wrapped gift strings.
 */
function wrapping(gifts) {
    // Define the wrapping paper template
    const paper = '*****\n';

    // Create an array to store the wrapped gifts
    const wrapped = [];

    // Iterate over each gift
    gifts.forEach(gift => {
        // Add the gift to the wrapping paper template
        wrapped.push(paper.replace('*****', '*'+ gift +'*'));

        // Add the top and bottom corners
        wrapped.push('*' + paper.replace('*****','* ') + '*');
    });

    // Return the array of wrapped gifts
    return wrapped;
}

// Test the function
const gifts = ["cat", "game", "socks"];
console.log(wrapping(gifts));
```

When you run this code, it will output the wrapped gifts as shown in your example. The `wrapping` function takes an array of gift strings, wraps each gift with the given algorithm, and returns an array of wrapped gift strings. The `paper` variable defines the wrapping paper template, which includes the corners. The `forEach` loop iterates over each gift, adds it to the wrapping paper template, and adds the top and bottom corners. The `replace` method is used to replace the `*****` placeholder in the paper template with the gift string.
